About the project

Introduction to Open Data Science 2019

I am attending Introduction to Open Data Science (IODS) course fall 2019.

The course helps participants to understand possibilities of open science, open data, and open research tools. Here I will learn to use a few open software tools like R and GitHub, and to visualize and analyze data sets with some fairly advanced statistical methods.

My supervisor recommended this course to me, and I believe it will be very useful for me.

Dataset alc contains data collected from secondary school students. Data includes information on the students background, grades, and alcohol consumption. Find more information on the data from here.

Purpose of this analysis is to study the relationships between alcohol consumption and chosen variables in the data. I am interested in how the family, friends and romantic relationships affect the alcohol usage of the students, so I chose these four variables:

  • famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  • famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)
  • romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
  • goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

I hypothesize that the chosen variables and alcohol consumption have following relationships:

  • H1 Good family relations are connected to low alcohol usage
  • H2 Family educational support is connected to low alcohol usage
  • H3 Romantic relationship does not have a clear connection with alcohol usage
  • H4 Going out with friends is connected to high alcohol usage

Barplot shows that observations of alcohol usage is skewed so that there are much more observations of low alcohol consuption, thus there are also more false observations of high alcohol use. Variable goout is normally distributed, whereas famrel is slightly skewed to higher values, meaning that most students have good family relations in this dataset. Additionally, most students are not in a romantic relationship and most get educational support from their families.

Logistic regression (task 5)

# find the model with glm()
m <- glm(high_use ~ goout + famsup + famrel + romantic, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# print out a summary of the model
summary(m)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ goout + famsup + famrel + romantic, 
##     family = "binomial", data = alc)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.6331  -0.7741  -0.5625   0.9753   2.4552  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -1.8194     0.6408  -2.839  0.00452 ** 
## goout         0.7956     0.1186   6.711 1.94e-11 ***
## famsupyes    -0.1546     0.2493  -0.620  0.53506    
## famrel       -0.3770     0.1338  -2.818  0.00483 ** 
## romanticyes  -0.2774     0.2657  -1.044  0.29650    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 465.68  on 381  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 406.60  on 377  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 416.6
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4
# print out the coefficients of the model
coef(m)
## (Intercept)       goout   famsupyes      famrel romanticyes 
##  -1.8194377   0.7956040  -0.1546234  -0.3769937  -0.2773591

Based on the model, going out with friends is positively correlated (estimate of coefficient = 0.7956) with higher alcohol usage, and it is also statistically significant (p<0.001) Model also shows that good family relations correlate negatively (estimate of coefficient = -0.3770) with high alcohol usage with significance of p<0.01. Having family support on studies and romantic relationship both correlated negatively but unsignificantly with high alcohol consumption.

Conclusions: Students who often go out with their friends are more likely to consume higher amounts of alcohol than the ones who dont go out so often. Also, students with good family relations are less likely high alcohol consumers compared to those who have worse relationship with their families. Thus, hypotheses H1, H3, and H4 were confirmed.

# compute odds ratios (OR) and confidence intervals (CI)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp

# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)

Binary predictions (task 6)

# fit the model
m <- glm(high_use ~ famrel+ goout, data = alc, family = "binomial")
# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")
# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)
# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   243   25
##    TRUE     68   46

Based on the table above, training error can be calculated: (68+25)/382 = 0,243455 = 24 %. This means that the model correctly predicted the alcohol usage of the students in 76 % of the cases.
